  "response_text": "The opening visible image is a close-up of fried chicken on a plate, with large white words across the center reading “We Do Chicken Right.” It lasts only briefly before the scene changes completely.\n\nThe Velveeta portion opens on a brightly colored, miniature Mexican-style plaza set against a painted desert sunset, with pink-orange sky, dark mountains, rocky buildings, and cactus shapes in the distance. Two large Velveeta Mexican product boxes sit like storefronts at the back of the plaza. Both packages show the green Velveeta logo in a white oval over a photo of melted cheese on food. The left package has a purple diagonal label ending in “Mexican,” while the right package has a green diagonal label that reads “Mild Mexican.” In front of the boxes are tiny tables, chairs, and decorative lights, making the packages look like little cantinas or market stalls.\n\nIn the foreground and across the plaza, animated green jalapeño peppers act like little dancers. Each pepper stands upright like a body, with a colorful sombrero tilted on top. The hats are red, green, yellow, blue, and purple, with zigzag and starburst decorations. The peppers bob, sway, and turn as if dancing in a fiesta. Some hats tilt forward like faces, and others spin or dip as the peppers move across the stone-patterned floor. Large chunks and curls of pale yellow cheese sit around the edges of the set, reinforcing that the action is taking place in a playful cheese-and-Mexican-snack world.\n\nThe view moves closer to the dancing peppers. A group of them crosses in front of the Velveeta boxes, their sombreros filling more of the picture. One wears a wide orange-red sombrero, another a green hat with yellow zigzags, and another a small red-and-white patterned hat. Their glossy green pepper bodies bounce from side to side, with the hats dipping and lifting in rhythm. A few red droplets or bits appear around the orange hat as it spins, adding to the lively animated movement.\n\nThe setting then shifts to a closer area in front of a mound of Velveeta-like cheese pieces: cubes, blocks, and soft curls piled high in the background. The pepper dancers continue moving among the cheese. White legal text appears at the lower left: “©1988 KRAFT Inc. Pasteurized Process Cheese Spread.” The jalapeños still wear sombreros, turning and bobbing between the cheese chunks. One sombrero is purple-rimmed with a small crown-like center; another is yellow-green with red markings around the brim. They weave past each other as if parading through the cheese landscape.\n\nThe scene returns to a wider view of the miniature plaza, with the two Velveeta boxes again in the background and the pepper dancers spread across the center. Soon a real plate of nachos enters the foreground from the right, much larger than the tiny animated set behind it. The plate is piled with tortilla chips covered in melted golden cheese, black olive slices, and small red diced toppings. The product boxes remain behind the nachos, now functioning as a backdrop.\n\nA light-skinned human hand reaches in from the right side above the plate. Only the hand and part of the wrist are visible. The fingers hover over the chips, then pinch one tortilla chip that is coated with melted cheese and topped with small red pieces and a black olive slice. The hand lifts the chip upward, stretching it away from the pile. The two Velveeta Mexican boxes stay clearly visible behind the plate, with the Velveeta logos facing forward. At the bottom of the screen, large white on-screen text appears reading “¡Velveeta Mexican!” as the hand holds the loaded nacho chip above the plate.",
